nexttext:
\end{subequations}
\noindent where $\delta_\nu$, $q_\nu$, $\pi_\nu$, $F_{\nu,\ell}$ are the moments of the neutrino distribution function, ${\ensuremath{c^2_{\textrm{eff}}}}$ is the adiabatic sound speed in the cosmic neutrino background rest frame and ${\ensuremath{c^2_{\textrm{vis}}}}$ is the ``viscosity'' parameter which parameterizes the anisotropic stress. For standard neutrinos, we have ${\ensuremath{c^2_{\textrm{eff}}}}={\ensuremath{c^2_{\textrm{vis}}}}=1/3$. Constraints on these parameters have been set by several authors (see e.g. \citep{Ade:2015xua,Gerbino:2013ova,Archidiacono:2013lva,Diamanti:2012tg,smith12}), since the observation of deviations from the standard values could suggest non-standard physics. As pointed out by \citet{Sellentin:2014gaa,Oldengott:2014qra}, it is difficult to give a clear physical interpretation of models with ${\ensuremath{c^2_{\textrm{vis}}}}$ and ${\ensuremath{c^2_{\textrm{eff}}}}$ different from the standard expected values. Nevertheless, the set of Eqs.~\eqref{eq:perturbations} captures the general behavior of the neutrino fluid around the free streaming regime ${\ensuremath{c^2_{\textrm{vis}}}}={\ensuremath{c^2_{\textrm{eff}}}}=1/3$ and therefore this simple approach can be exploited to test the  validity of the canonical assumptions for the neutrino perturbation parameters. \citet{Gerbino:2013ova} have pointed out the existing degeneracy between the neutrino perturbations and the inflationary parameters. In particular, it can be shown, as illustrated Fig.~\ref{fig:tri_pps_nupert}, that the main degeneracies arise between the following pairs of parameters: ${\ensuremath{c^2_{\textrm{vis}}}}$ and $10^9\,A_s\,e^{-2\tau}$ (i.e.\ the damped amplitude of the CMB power spectrum); ${\ensuremath{c^2_{\textrm{eff}}}}$ and $n_S$. In the former case, the impact of ${\ensuremath{c^2_{\textrm{vis}}}}$ on the power spectrum shape is an overall rescaling, while, in the latter case, ${\ensuremath{c^2_{\textrm{eff}}}}$ is responsible for a relative modulation of the acoustic peaks. Therefore, it seems natural to test the stability of the constraints on ${\ensuremath{c^2_{\textrm{vis}}}}$ and ${\ensuremath{c^2_{\textrm{eff}}}}$ by adopting a different parameterization for the PPS. 

\subsection{Results}
We find here the same the degeneracy between ${\ensuremath{c^2_{\textrm{vis}}}}$, ${\ensuremath{c^2_{\textrm{eff}}}}$ and the parameters governing the shape of the primordial power spectrum reported in \citet{Gerbino:2013ova}. In particular, as shown in Fig.~\ref{fig:tri_pchip_nupert}, the degeneracies involve the nodes between ${\ensuremath{P_{s,{7}}}}$ and ${\ensuremath{P_{s,{10}}}}$, corresponding to scales in the multipole range $150\leq\ell\leq2500$. We have checked that the limits on ${\ensuremath{P_{s,{i}}}}$ with $i\le4$ obtained by marginalizing over ${\ensuremath{c^2_{\textrm{vis}}}}$ and ${\ensuremath{c^2_{\textrm{eff}}}}$ are consistent with their limits in the minimal ${\ensuremath{\Lambda\textrm{CDM}}\xspace}$ model with standard neutrino perturbations (i.e., fixing ${\ensuremath{c^2_{\textrm{vis}}}}={\ensuremath{c^2_{\textrm{eff}}}}=1/3$). On the other hand, the bounds on ${\ensuremath{P_{s,{i}}}}$ with $i\ge5$ become broader with a shift of the mean value of the posterior distribution toward higher amplitudes with respect to the ${\ensuremath{\Lambda\textrm{CDM}}\xspace}$ case. This behavior is consistent with what we found assuming the classical power-law PPS after marginalizing over ${\ensuremath{c^2_{\textrm{vis}}}}$ and ${\ensuremath{c^2_{\textrm{eff}}}}$: also in this case the preferred values for the scalar tilt $n_S$ and the scalar amplitude $A_s$ are greater than the corresponding values in the standard ${\ensuremath{\Lambda\textrm{CDM}}\xspace}$ scenario (see Tabs.~\ref{tab:nupert_TT1} and \ref{tab:nupert_TTTEEE1} for details).

Concerning the degeneracy between $\Omega_c h^2$ and $H_0$ discussed in the previous sections, it is consistent with the direction arising in the standard ${\ensuremath{\Lambda\textrm{CDM}}\xspace}$ model, since the model investigated in this section does not modify the different background quantities.  The impact of ${\ensuremath{c^2_{\textrm{vis}}}}$ and $\Omega_c h^2$ on the CMB power spectra is similar, leading to a degeneracy in the ${\ensuremath{c^2_{\textrm{vis}}}}-\Omega_c h^2$ plane (compare e.g.\ the behavior of the posterior distributions for the two parameters in Fig.~\ref{fig:1d_pchip_nupert}, where it is clear that the two distributions change consistently). We note that marginalizing over the neutrino anisotropy parameters results in constraints on $\Omega_c h^2$ which remain stable versus the different datasets considered in the analyses, see Tabs.~\ref{tab:nupert_TT1} and \ref{tab:nupert_TTTEEE1}. 

