\subsubsection{Planck TT,TE,EE+lowP}
We report our results from the Planck TT,TE,EE+lowP dataset alone and combined with external datasets in Tab.~\ref{tab:nupert_TTTEEE1}, while Fig.~\ref{fig:1d_pol_pchip_nupert} shows the one-dimensional posterior probabilities for the most relevant cosmological parameters. The inclusion of the CMB small scale polarization allows to tighten the constraints quoted above. The dramatic increase in sensitivity (especially for the case of the ${\ensuremath{c^2_{\textrm{vis}}}}$ parameter) has been already pointed out and discussed in \citet{Ade:2015xua}. Here, we would like to draw the attention to other issues. Namely, it is worth noticing that CMB polarization plays a crucial role in constraining small scale nodes, making possible to get bounds on ${\ensuremath{P_{s,{11}}}}$ (${\ensuremath{P_{s,{11}}}}=2.5^{+2.0}_{-2.4}$ at 95\% CL for CMB alone. The inclusion of BAO marginally increases the sensitivity to these parameters, in contrast to what previously discussed. On the other hand, the combination CMB+MPkW results in the most stringent constraints, given the small-scale range covered by the MPkW measurements, matching the results in the case without high-$\ell$ polarization data.

Finally, when considering the results from CMB+lensing, it has to be highlighted that this specific combination of datasets shows a mild tension for what concerns the posterior distributions of $\Omega_ch^2$, $\tau$ and ${\ensuremath{P_{s,{i}}}}$ with $5\le i\le10$. This could be probably due to the preference for a lower value of $A_s$, already present in the Planck TT+lensing combination presented above, which is responsible for dragging down the posterior on $\tau$ and ${\ensuremath{P_{s,{i}}}}$, at least for the scales most sensitive to the usual $\tau-A_s$ combination.

Focusing on the neutrino perturbations, the constraints on ${\ensuremath{c^2_{\textrm{eff}}}}$ are very stable against a change in both the combination of datasets and the PPS parameterization chosen for the analysis. On the other hand, the peak of the posterior distribution of ${\ensuremath{c^2_{\textrm{vis}}}}$ is considerably shifted towards lower values when replacing the classical power-law PPS shape by the {\texttt{PCHIP}\xspace} PPS parameterization. However, the posterior is very stable against the dataset choice when fixing the PPS shape. As in the analysis including Planck TT+lowP only, the bounds on ${\ensuremath{c^2_{\textrm{vis}}}}$ are broadened  by more than 25\% for each dataset when considering the {\texttt{PCHIP}\xspace} parameterization. This is due to the fact that, while in the power-law case the inclusion of CMB polarization at small scales greatly helps in constraining $n_s$ and $A_s$, in the {\texttt{PCHIP}\xspace} parameterization the parameter space is wider than in the PPS case, with more degeneracies to be alleviated. The small scale polarization seems to prefer lower values for the ${\ensuremath{P_{s,{i}}}}$ nodes, which in turn are responsible for the lower values obtained for ${\ensuremath{c^2_{\textrm{vis}}}}$ (when comparing to the case without high multipole polarization data).



